[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:immer-immutable/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
